    - candidate: spot-the-shifter-or-absorber-pattern (correct-the-bias)
        - location: lines 3066-3098 (the section "It Helps Correct Our Tendency to Shift or Absorb"), with the Blame Absorbers subsection at 3072-3083 (the launch-failure case, the resentment-build, and the abusive-relationship note) and the Blame Shifters subsection at 3089-3098 (the venture-capital-pitch case and the victim-stance dynamic).
        - paraphrase: receivers fall into two opposite habitual stances. The blame absorber, when feedback arrives, points the finger at themselves for the whole thing ("I screwed up the launch single-handedly") — which feels noble but obstructs learning by stopping the inquiry once your own contribution is named, lets others off the hook, and can build resentment or trap you in abusive dynamics. The blame shifter, when feedback arrives, blames everyone else ("the VCs are fools, the markets are impossible") — which feels relaxing but produces a victim-stance from which nothing can be learned and nothing changed. The receiver-side move: identify which profile is firing in this moment, and use the systems view to deliberately correct against your bias. Absorbers ask "what else (beyond me) is contributing?"; shifters ask "what am I contributing?"
        - situation: feedback has landed and you can feel yourself sliding into a habitual response — either rushing to take it all on ("you're right, I screwed up, my fault") or batting it away ("none of this is on me, they're the problem"). The systems-thinking diagnostic is what corrects the bias.
        - outcome: → promoted to spot-the-shifter-or-absorber-pattern. Distinct from take-three-steps-back (which is the diagnostic toolkit for mapping the dynamic). This skill operates earlier and on a different layer: it identifies the *receiver's habitual stance* (absorb everything / shift everything) before the diagnostic is even applied, and uses the diagnostic as the corrective. Distinct from name-both-needs (the learn/accept tension) and from separate-impact-from-intent (intent vs impact asymmetry within yourself). The two profiles are explicitly named, each has its own failure mode (learning blocked, resentment, abuse-trap; or victim-stance, no learning, exhaustion), and the corrective action is concrete (run the systems diagnostic with bias-aware prompting). Strong gate.

    - candidate: take-responsibility-first-then-introduce-the-system
        - location: lines 3143-3148 (the "Take Responsibility for Your Part" section with the explicit two-message structure and the sequencing prescription), continued in 3146 ("Otherwise the giver will hear your suggestion to look at 'our relationship system' as making excuses").
        - paraphrase: when introducing a systems view to a giver who came in with one-sided feedback, the order matters: lead by acknowledging your own contribution, let that land, *then* circle back to discuss the broader dynamic and your observations and requests of them. Two messages have to be sent ("I take responsibility for my part" and "we are both contributing to this"), but to the giver they can sound contradictory if delivered together; sequencing them prevents the second from being heard as a deflection of the first.
